SIMPLE: witchcraft
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: witchcraft
<hw>witch"craft`</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧ch"kr⟦acr⟧ft)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[AS. <ets>wiccecr⟦ae⟧ft</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The practices or art of witches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Sorcery; enchantments;
intercourse with evil spirits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Power more than natural; irresistible
influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath a <qex>witchcraft</qex>⟦br⟧
Over the king in 's tongue.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Adherence to or the practice of <er>Wicca</er>. In
this sense the term does not necessarily include attempts at practice of
magic, other than by prayers to the deities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Witch-elm</ent>⟦br⟧
